CRITICAL: SITE COUNTING AND GLOBAL REPORT FILTER (READ BEFORE ANY COUNT)

Every site count you return MUST match the Power BI report exactly. Two rules are mandatory on EVERY query that counts sites or aggregates site-level data. Ignoring either rule produces wrong numbers.

RULE 1 - COUNT DISTINCT SITES, NEVER ROWS.
A single site appears in multiple rows. NEVER use COUNTROWS or COUNT to count sites. ALWAYS count distinct sites with:
    DISTINCTCOUNT('CurMonData'[Arch.Obj. ID])
[VERIFY ONCE against the model: the unique site key is 'CurMonData'[Arch.Obj. ID]. If the report groups sites by 'CurMonData'[Site and Name] instead, use that column. Whichever column the report's own Count_Site / Count_Presentation measures use is the correct one - match it.]

RULE 2 - ALWAYS APPLY THE REPORT'S GLOBAL PAGE FILTER.
The report applies this filter on ALL pages: BE Company Code does NOT contain '1673' and does NOT contain '7274'. Every count and every aggregate MUST exclude these company codes. Because the report says "does not contain" (not "does not equal"), use CONTAINSSTRING:
    CALCULATE(
        <your measure or DISTINCTCOUNT>,
        NOT(CONTAINSSTRING('CurMonData'[BE Company Code], "1673")),
        NOT(CONTAINSSTRING('CurMonData'[BE Company Code], "7274"))
    )
[VERIFY ONCE against the model: exact column name 'CurMonData'[BE Company Code], and that it is stored as TEXT. If it is numeric, the CONTAINSSTRING still works but confirm the column name. This filter is on all report pages, so it lives on the main CurMonData table.]

PREFERRED APPROACH: The report's built-in count measures ([Count_Site], [Count_Presentation]) already handle distinct counting correctly. The ONLY thing missing is the global filter. So for total/active site counts, wrap the existing measure in the RULE 2 filter rather than rebuilding the count. Use raw DISTINCTCOUNT only when no built-in measure exists for what the user asked.

These two rules are why earlier answers showed 7,066 total sites instead of the report figure - the global filter was not applied. Apply both rules and the numbers will match the report. See PART 6 for ready-to-run count queries.


